        "heading": "Clinical Note",
        "section_value": "Chief Complaint\nHeadache and elevated blood pressure.\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports a long-standing history of elevated blood pressure, for which he was previously prescribed chlorthalidone, which he discontinued due to gastrointestinal side effects. He also experiences intermittent headaches, primarily on the top of his head, which are throbbing and provide some relief with acetaminophen. He reports occasional dizziness and blurred vision associated with these headaches. He has been taking his medications irregularly, approximately every other day.\nFindings\nVital signs reveal a blood pressure of 172/98 mmHg. The patient reports slight edema in the upper extremities and a one+ pitting edema in the lower extremities. Examination reveals a systolic ejection murmur of II/VI, which is consistent with the murmur noted last year. Lung auscultation is clear bilaterally. Carotid bruits are absent. Oxygen saturation is within normal limits.\nAssessment\nUncontrolled hypertension and headache.\nPlan",
